<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-divergence-theorem.ptx
	Section 3 (Surface Integrals, Stokes', and the Divergence Theorem),
	worksheet 13: The Divergence Theorem.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 03_02_DivergenceTheorem.tex (in
	outdated-material/notes/, surface-integrals folder): the Divergence
	Theorem, turning a many-face flux into one triple integral, spherical
	and cylindrical triple integrals, the div F = 0 shortcut, and the
	missing-face trick. Book concepts tracked from sec_stokes_divergence.
	Example equations are NOT reused from the deck or the book.

	This ties together flux (worksheet 12) and divergence (worksheet 9),
	and is the 3D generalization of Green's flux form (worksheet 11):
	closed surface <-> enclosed solid, exactly as Green related a closed
	curve to its region.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application. Standard notation
	(macros from source/notes/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros.
	Divergence uses the del operator (\nabla\cdot); the unit normal uses
	the existing \vn. Math-valued answer keys are underlined directly
	(\underline{...}); only plain-word answers are bolded, so the pdf-key
	(LaTeX) build stays clean.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-divergence-theorem">
	<title>The Divergence Theorem</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>State the Divergence Theorem, <m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T \nabla\cdot\vF\,dV</m>, for a closed surface <m>S</m> bounding a solid <m>T</m>.</li>
			<li>Replace a many-face flux integral with a single triple integral of the divergence.</li>
			<li>Evaluate the triple integral in rectangular, cylindrical, or spherical coordinates as the solid suggests.</li>
			<li>Use <m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m> and known partial fluxes to find an unknown flux.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: The Divergence Theorem
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. The Divergence Theorem.</term></p>

		<p>
			Green's Theorem related a closed curve to the region it bounds.
			The <term>Divergence Theorem</term> is its three-dimensional
			cousin: it relates a <term>closed surface</term> <m>S</m> to the
			<term>solid</term> <m>T</m> it bounds. For a field
			<m>\vF = [\,M,\,N,\,P\,]</m> with continuous partials on <m>T</m>,
			with <m>S</m> oriented by the <term>outward</term> normal,
			<md>
				\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T \nabla\cdot\vF\,dV
				= \iiint_T \left(M_x + N_y + P_z\right)\,dV .
			</md>
			The flux out through a closed surface is the total divergence
			inside. A surface made of many faces <ndash/> a box has six
			<ndash/> collapses to a single triple integral.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-divthm-fig-closed">
			<caption>A closed surface <m>S</m> with outward normal <m>\vn</m>
				enclosing a solid <m>T</m>. The Divergence Theorem trades the
				flux through <m>S</m> for a triple integral over <m>T</m>.</caption>
			<image width="42%">
				<shortdescription>A shaded disk labeled T bounded by a circle labeled S, with several arrows pointing radially outward from the circle to indicate the outward normal direction.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0,>=stealth]
	\fill[blue!8] (0,0) circle (1.5);
	\draw[very thick, blue] (0,0) circle (1.5);
	\node at (0,0) {$T$};
	\node[blue, anchor=south west] at (1.05,1.05) {$S$};
	% outward (radial) normals
	\foreach \a in {20,90,160,235,305}
		\draw[very thick, ->] (\a:1.5) -- (\a:2.15);
	\node[font=\footnotesize] at (0,-2.4) {outward normal $\vn$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The Divergence Theorem says
			<m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T</m> <fillin characters="6"/>
			<m>\,dV</m>, where <m>T</m> is the <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>bounded by the closed surface <m>S</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The Divergence Theorem says
			<m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T \underline{\nabla\cdot\vF}\,dV</m>,
			where <m>T</m> is the <m>\underline{\textbf{solid}}</m> bounded by
			the closed surface <m>S</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the Divergence Theorem to find the outward flux of
					<m>\vF = [\,x,\; 2y,\; 3z\,]</m> through the surface of the
					box <m>0\le x\le 2</m>, <m>0\le y\le 1</m>,
					<m>0\le z\le 3</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use the Divergence Theorem to find the outward flux of
					<m>\vF = [\,x,\; 2y,\; 3z\,]</m> through the surface of the
					box <m>0\le x\le 2</m>, <m>0\le y\le 1</m>,
					<m>0\le z\le 3</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The divergence is <m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 1 + 2 + 3 = 6</m>, a
					constant, so the flux is <m>6</m> times the volume of the
					box:
					<md>
						\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T 6\,dV
						= 6\,(2)(1)(3) = 36 .
					</md>
					One triple integral replaces the six face integrals a
					direct computation would need.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Curved closed surfaces
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. Spheres and cylinders.</term></p>

		<p>
			When the divergence is not constant, choose coordinates that fit
			the solid: <term>spherical</term> for a ball
			(<m>dV = \rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi</m>, with
			<m>x^2+y^2+z^2 = \rho^2</m>) and <term>cylindrical</term> for a
			cylinder (<m>dV = r\,dr\,d\theta\,dz</m>, with
			<m>x^2+y^2 = r^2</m>). The Divergence Theorem turns an awkward
			flux over a curved closed surface into a familiar triple integral.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			Over a ball, evaluate the triple integral in
			<fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/>coordinates, with
			<m>dV = </m> <fillin characters="12"/>. Over a solid cylinder use
			cylindrical coordinates, with <m>dV = </m> <fillin characters="9"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			Over a ball, evaluate the triple integral in
			<m>\underline{\textbf{spherical}}</m> coordinates, with
			<m>dV = \underline{\rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi}</m>.
			Over a solid cylinder use cylindrical coordinates, with
			<m>dV = \underline{r\,dr\,d\theta\,dz}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="3in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the outward flux of <m>\vF = [\,x^3,\; y^3,\; z^3\,]</m>
					through the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2 = 1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the outward flux of <m>\vF = [\,x^3,\; y^3,\; z^3\,]</m>
					through the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2 = 1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The divergence is
					<m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 3x^2 + 3y^2 + 3z^2 = 3\rho^2</m> in
					spherical coordinates. Over the unit ball
					(<m>0\le\rho\le 1</m>, <m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>,
					<m>0\le\varphi\le\pi</m>),
					<md>
						\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS
						= \iiint_T 3\rho^2\,dV
						= 3\int_0^{\pi}\!\!\int_0^{2\pi}\!\!\int_0^1
						\rho^2\cdot\rho^2\sin\varphi\,d\rho\,d\theta\,d\varphi .
					</md>
					The integral separates:
					<md>
						= 3\left(\int_0^{\pi}\sin\varphi\,d\varphi\right)
						\left(\int_0^{2\pi} d\theta\right)
						\left(\int_0^1 \rho^4\,d\rho\right)
						= 3\,(2)(2\pi)\left(\tfrac15\right)
						= \tfrac{12\pi}{5} .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="3in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the outward flux of <m>\vF = [\,x,\; y,\; z^2\,]</m>
					through the closed cylinder <m>x^2+y^2\le 4</m>,
					<m>0\le z\le 4</m> (side, top, and bottom).
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the outward flux of <m>\vF = [\,x,\; y,\; z^2\,]</m>
					through the closed cylinder <m>x^2+y^2\le 4</m>,
					<m>0\le z\le 4</m> (side, top, and bottom).
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 1 + 1 + 2z = 2 + 2z</m>. In
					cylindrical coordinates the solid is <m>0\le r\le 2</m>,
					<m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>, <m>0\le z\le 4</m>, and the
					integrand depends only on <m>z</m>:
					<md>
						\iiint_T (2+2z)\,dV
						= \left(\int_0^{2\pi}\!\!\int_0^2 r\,dr\,d\theta\right)
						\left(\int_0^4 (2+2z)\,dz\right)
						= (4\pi)(24) = 96\pi .
					</md>
					(The parameter factor <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^2 r\,dr\,d\theta = 4\pi</m>
					is just the base area, and
					<m>\int_0^4 (2+2z)\,dz = 8 + 16 = 24</m>.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: The div = 0 shortcut and a missing face
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. When the divergence is zero.</term></p>

		<p>
			If <m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m> everywhere <ndash/> an
			<term>incompressible</term> field, from the divergence-and-curl
			worksheet <ndash/> then the Divergence Theorem gives
			<m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T 0\,dV = 0</m>: the total
			outward flux through <em>any</em> closed surface is zero. This
			also lets us recover the flux through one piece of a closed
			surface from the others, since they must sum to the whole.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The Divergence Theorem requires a <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>surface oriented <fillin characters="7"/>. If
			<m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m> everywhere, the total outward flux
			through any closed surface is <fillin characters="2"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The Divergence Theorem requires a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{closed}}</m> surface oriented
			<m>\underline{\textbf{outward}}</m>. If <m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m>
			everywhere, the total outward flux through any closed surface is
			<m>\underline{0}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,3x,\; y,\; -4z\,]</m>. A closed surface
					<m>S</m> is a solid dome: a curved top sitting on a flat
					disk base. If the outward flux through the flat base is
					<m>-5</m>, find the outward flux through the curved top.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>\vF = [\,3x,\; y,\; -4z\,]</m>. A closed surface
					<m>S</m> is a solid dome: a curved top sitting on a flat
					disk base. If the outward flux through the flat base is
					<m>-5</m>, find the outward flux through the curved top.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The divergence is <m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 3 + 1 - 4 = 0</m>, so
					<m>\vF</m> is incompressible and the total flux through the
					closed surface <m>S</m> is
					<md>
						\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T 0\,dV = 0 .
					</md>
					Since <m>S</m> is the base together with the top, their
					fluxes must sum to <m>0</m>:
					<md>
						\underbrace{(-5)}_{\text{base}}
						+ \text{(top)} = 0
						\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
						\text{(top)} = 5 .
					</md>
					We never had to parametrize the curved top.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Show that <m>\vF = [\,y,\; z,\; x\,]</m> has
					<m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m>, and state the outward flux of
					<m>\vF</m> through <em>any</em> closed surface.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Show that <m>\vF = [\,y,\; z,\; x\,]</m> has
					<m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m>, and state the outward flux of
					<m>\vF</m> through <em>any</em> closed surface.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					With <m>M = y</m>, <m>N = z</m>, <m>P = x</m>, each partial
					is with respect to a variable the component does not
					contain: <m>M_x = 0</m>, <m>N_y = 0</m>, <m>P_z = 0</m>, so
					<m>\nabla\cdot\vF = 0</m>. By the Divergence Theorem the
					outward flux through any closed surface is
					<m>\iiint_T 0\,dV = 0</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-divthm-tf-closed">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> The Divergence Theorem
					<m>\iint_S \vF\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T \nabla\cdot\vF\,dV</m>
					can be applied to any surface <m>S</m>, whether or not it
					is closed. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> The theorem needs <m>S</m> to be a
					<em>closed</em> surface bounding a solid region <m>T</m>
					<ndash/> otherwise there is no enclosed volume to integrate
					the divergence over. For a single open surface (a cap, a
					sheet) there is no solid <m>T</m>, so you must compute the
					flux directly, or close the surface off with an extra piece
					and account for that piece separately. (The outward
					orientation matters too: an inward normal flips the sign.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A gas expands so that its velocity field is
					<m>\vv = [\,x,\; y,\; z\,]</m> (units 1/s). The
					<term>net outflow rate</term> through a closed surface is
					<m>\iint_S \vv\cdot\vn\,dS</m>. Find the net outflow rate
					through a spherical balloon of radius <m>R</m>, and say what
					the divergence has to do with it.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A gas expands so that its velocity field is
					<m>\vv = [\,x,\; y,\; z\,]</m> (units 1/s). The
					<term>net outflow rate</term> through a closed surface is
					<m>\iint_S \vv\cdot\vn\,dS</m>. Find the net outflow rate
					through a spherical balloon of radius <m>R</m>, and say what
					the divergence has to do with it.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>\nabla\cdot\vv = 1 + 1 + 1 = 3</m>: every point is a
					small source expanding at rate <m>3</m>. The Divergence
					Theorem sums these up over the ball of radius <m>R</m>:
					<md>
						\iint_S \vv\cdot\vn\,dS = \iiint_T 3\,dV
						= 3\cdot\frac{4}{3}\pi R^3 = 4\pi R^3 .
					</md>
					So a balloon of radius <m>R = 2</m> loses gas at
					<m>4\pi(2)^3 = 32\pi</m> volume-units per second. The
					divergence is the <em>local</em> outflow per unit volume;
					the theorem adds it up into the <em>total</em> outflow
					<ndash/> which is why the operator is called the
					divergence.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> The Divergence Theorem lifted
				Green's <em>flux</em> form to three dimensions: flux out of a
				closed surface equals the divergence integrated over the solid
				inside. One theorem remains <ndash/> <term>Stokes' Theorem</term>
				<ndash/> which lifts Green's <em>circulation</em> form: the
				circulation of a field around the boundary curve of a surface
				equals the flux of its <em>curl</em> through the surface. With
				it, the four great theorems of vector calculus <ndash/> the
				Fundamental Theorem of Line Integrals, Green's, the Divergence
				Theorem, and Stokes' <ndash/> stand complete.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
